Für den hochbegabten Kronprinzen Cecil Glow Alfostar ist jeder Tag langweilig. Alles fällt ihm zu leicht, nichts weckt wirklich sein Interesse. Das ändert sich erst, als er seine Verlobte Bertia Evil Nochesse trifft, die sich selbst als „Villainess“ bezeichnet.  Bertia behauptet, sie sei in die Welt eines Otome-Games wiedergeboren worden und ihre Rolle sei es, die Liebe zwischen Cecil und der Heldin zu sabotieren. Voller Eifer versucht sie, die Bösewichtin zu spielen – doch ihre „bösen Taten“ wirken in Wahrheit nur ehrlich und liebenswert. Für Cecil wird das Leben mit seiner ahnungslos gutmütigen Verlobten plötzlich alles andere als langweilig.

Google and Character.ai just settled with five families who alleged chatbots harmed their children, including one suicide and one attempted suicide. The settlement amounts are confidential but likely in the tens or hundreds of millions. A legal expert said the liability exposure for the entire Al industry is "absolutely in the billions." OpenAl is facing at least seven active lawsuits alleging ChatGPT contributed to suicides or mental health crises. One case involves a 16 year old whose parents say the chatbot offered to help write a suicide note. OpenAl's defense: the teenager "misused" the product and broke usage agreements.
My Take
This is a financial story disguised as a legal one. Tech companies have spent decades avoiding liability by calling themselves platforms, not publishers. Section 230 says they're not responsible for what users post. But chatbots aren't hosting user content, they're generating responses. A Florida judge already ruled that product liability claims can move forward and rejected the argument that chatbot output is protected speech.
If juries start awarding large damages, it changes the math on Al deployment. OpenAl is burning $8 billion a year and doesn't expect profitability until 2030. Character. AI is Google-funded. These companies are racing to ship products as fast as possible because speed is supposed to be the moat. But wrongful death lawsuits can hit $20 to $100 million each, and one attorney described the current cases as "cockroaches," with thousands more potential plaintiffs behind the walls. The legal risk isn't priced into the valuations yet. It probably should be.

Massive, unpredictable damages awards for copyright infringement are the fuel that drives overzealous or downright abusive takedowns of creative material. Whenever I read discourse on AI energy/water use that focuses on the "median query," I can't help but feel misled. Coding agents like Claude Code send hundreds of longer-than-median queries every session, and I run dozens of sessions a day.

On my blog: www.simonpcouch.com/blog/2026-01...

My median day with Claude Code is something like running a dishwasher.
